    bio: 'Dhovemi, the second sovereign of the Maldives, presided over the single most consequential event in the archipelago\'s history: the conversion of the islands from Buddhism to Islam in 1153 CE. His full Sanskritic regnal style, Svasti Sri Sandanayaka Tribhuwana Aditya Maha Radun (Bavanaadheeththa), marks him as the last Maldivian ruler to bear a purely Indic title before the adoption of Arabic nomenclature. After conversion, he took the Islamic name Sultan Muhammad al-Adil, meaning "The Just," becoming the first Muslim monarch of the Maldives.\n\nDhovemi was the son of Henevi Ma\'ava\'a Kilege, the sister of the founding sovereign Koimala, making him Koimala\'s nephew. His father\'s personal name is not recorded in the surviving chronicles, reflecting the strongly matrilineal character of early Maldivian succession patterns. He succeeded his uncle before July 26, 1142, and his pre-conversion reign of approximately eleven years saw the continuation of the Buddhist-Sinhalese political order that had characterized the Maldives for centuries.\n\nThe conversion to Islam on July 7, 1153 is attributed in competing traditions to different figures. The Moroccan traveler Ibn Battuta, who visited the Maldives nearly two centuries later, credited Abu\'l-Baraka\'at the Berber, a North African holy man who supposedly expelled a sea-demon (rannamaari) that terrorized the islanders. The local Tarikh tradition, however, credits Abul Rikab Yusuf Shams ud-din with the conversion. Whatever the historical mechanism, the shift from Buddhism to Islam was rapid and thoroughgoing, transforming not only the religious identity but also the political vocabulary, legal framework, and cultural orientation of the entire archipelago.\n\nAfter a reign of approximately twenty-five years, Dhovemi did not die in the Maldives but departed on pilgrimage to Mecca before October 28, 1166, never to return. This departure for the holy cities, whether voluntary abdication or political exile dressed in pious garb, established a pattern that would recur in Maldivian royal history: sultans departing the islands and never resuming their thrones. His post-conversion Arabic title Sultan Muhammad al-Adil ibn Abdullah reflects the standard Islamic convention of assigning "ibn Abdullah" (son of a servant of God) to converts whose fathers were not Muslim, a practice that would mark the first generation of Maldivian Islamic rulers.\n\nDhovemi\'s legacy is foundational. Every subsequent Maldivian sovereign would rule as a Muslim monarch, and the Islamic identity he inaugurated has persisted unbroken to the present day. The traditional chronicle accounts honor him with the epithet Dharumavantha Rasgefaanu, and he is remembered as the sovereign who brought the light of Islam to the scattered coral islands of the Indian Ocean.'
