    bio: 'Mohamed el-Jameel, known in Arabic as Sultan Muhammad Jamil ud-din, was the twenty-first sovereign of the Maldives and the first husband of the formidable Sultana Khadijah (P20). His full titulature, Svasti Sri Buwana Suriya Maha Radun, combined the traditional Sanskritic regnal style with his Arabic name, reflecting the dual naming conventions of fourteenth-century Maldivian royalty. Ibn Battuta identifies him as the wazir (chief minister) who helped Khadijah seize power from her brother Ahmad Shihab al-Din (P19) in 1347.\n\nJameel\'s origins are obscure. Some secondary accounts attach the epithet "al-Misri" (the Egyptian), suggesting a possible North African provenance, though this geographic attribution remains uncertain. What is clear is that he served as Grand Vizier before his elevation to the sultanate through marriage to the ruling queen. He had children from a previous marriage, including a son Muhammad Ha\'adiyari Khatib and a daughter who later married Ibn Battuta himself.\n\nJameel\'s reign was brief and ended in his death before January 7, 1345. The Maldivian chronicle tradition, corroborated by Ibn Battuta\'s account, holds that Khadijah arranged his assassination, establishing a grim pattern that would repeat with her second husband Abdullah (P23). His Arabic name Jamil ud-din, meaning "Beauty of the Faith," rendered in the project data as "el-Jameel," preserves the same Arabic root j-m-l that appears across both forms.'
