    bio: 'Abdullah ibn Muhammad al-Hadhrami, the twenty-third sovereign of the Maldives, was Khadijah\'s second husband-sultan and, like his predecessor Jameel (P21), met his end at her hands. His nisba "al-Hadhrami" indicates origins in the Hadhramaut region of Yemen, connecting him to the networks of Hadhrami merchants and scholars who served as major vectors of Islamic influence across the Indian Ocean from East Africa to Southeast Asia.\n\nAbdullah was the son of Muhammad al-Hadhrami, the powerful vizier who had served as regent during the reign of Ahmad Shihab al-Din (P19). Before his elevation to the sultanate, Abdullah had a complex marital history: he had married a daughter of Sultan Muhammad Jamil ud-din (P21), been divorced, and then married the widow of Sultan Omar Veeru (P18) around 1342. His marriage to Sultana Khadijah (P20) in 1345 brought him to the throne as her consort-sultan.\n\nAbdullah reigned from before June 13, 1374 until his murder before May 10, 1377. The Maldivian chronicles record that Khadijah had him killed "in bed," a detail that underscores the intimate and violent nature of court politics in the fourteenth-century sultanate. He left one daughter, whose name is not preserved in the sources. His Hadhramaut connection is historically significant beyond his personal fate, representing the broader pattern of Arab immigration that shaped the religious and cultural character of the post-conversion Maldives.'
