    source_refs: ['SRC-MRF-KINGS', 'SRC-WIKI-MONARCHS'],
    bio: 'Kalu Mohamed, the most tenacious claimant to the Hilaaly throne, ruled the Maldives across three separate accessions spanning nearly four decades (1492-1529), making him one of the most persistent political survivors in the archipelago\'s history. His popular sobriquet "Kalu Bandaarain" remained his enduring identifier in the chronicle traditions. His pre-accession title, Raddeba Magu Kalu Muhammad Manikufa\'anu, places him within the Hilaaly aristocratic naming conventions.\n\nKalu Mohamed was a son of Omar II (P46) by his third wife Sitti Rani Kilege, who was herself the maternal half-sister of Abu Bakar I (P40), creating a dense web of Hilaaly kinship connections. His first accession in 1492 lasted only nine months before he was deposed by his half-brother Yusuf III (P52). After Yusuf\'s death and the brief intervening reign of Ali IV (P53), Kalu Mohamed secured the throne a second time around 1496 and held it for approximately fifteen years until deposed by his nephew Hassan VII (P55) in 1510.\n\nHis third and final reign, beginning around 1514, was achieved with the military support of the Ali Raja of Cannanore and the Portuguese, inaugurating an era of increasing foreign entanglement in Maldivian politics. The Portuguese demanded annual tribute as the price of their support, marking the beginning of European commercial and political penetration of the archipelago. Kalu Mohamed married four wives in succession: an unnamed first wife, Buraki Rani (a daughter of P40 known for her martial arts prowess), Fatima Dio from Shiraz in Persia, and Amira Aisatu Kilege.\n\nKalu Mohamed died before August 25, 1530. His children shaped the next generation of Maldivian politics profoundly: his son Hassan VIII as-Shirazi (P59) by Fatima Dio succeeded him directly; his sons Umar Ma\'afai Kilege (P219) and Ahmad Manikufa\'anu Kalaminja (P220) fathered Mohamed (P60) and Hassan IX/Dom Manoel (P61) respectively; and his daughter Princess Aysha Rani Kilege (P208) married Ali VI (P63). Through these descendants, Kalu Mohamed\'s bloodline persisted through the Portuguese interregnum, the Utheemu liberation, and ultimately into the Huraagey dynasty that ruled the Maldives until 1968.'
