    bio: 'Mohamed Ghiyathuddine, bearing the Arabic laqab Ghiyath al-Din meaning "Succor of the Faith," was the last sultan of the Dhiyamigili dynasty and a figure remembered with both reverence and pathos. Born before October 6, 1733 at Kabafa\'anu Palace in Male, he was the son of Ibrahim Iskandar II (P78) and Aisha Kabafa\'anu. His popular epithet Haajee Bandaarain reflected his completion of the Hajj pilgrimage.\n\nHe came to the throne in 1766 as a Dhiyamigili restoration figure after the Huraagey founder Hassan Izzuddine (P80) died, representing an attempt to return the older dynasty to power. He married three times and fathered a son, Abdullah Ibrahim, born in 1760. Secondary sources credit him with compiling the first known Thaana dictionary, making him a figure of cultural as well as political significance.\n\nHis reign ended tragically when he drowned off Guraidu island on October 8, 1774. Some historical narratives remember him as Shaheed Kulha Bandaarain, a martyr ruler, suggesting that his death may not have been entirely accidental. His drowning definitively ended the Dhiyamigili dynasty and restored the Huraagey line to permanent power.'
