    source_refs: ['SRC-WIKI-MUHAMMAD-FAREED'],
    bio: 'Mohamed Farid, the last sultan of the Maldives, presided over the transformation of a centuries-old monarchy into a modern republic. Born in 1901 at Male, he was the son of Amir Amin Abdul-Majid Didi (P111), whose own connection to the royal house ran through the Athireegey (Huraagey collateral) family. His mother, Princess Veyoge Don Goma (also known as Ruqia Don Goma), was a daughter of Sultan Ibrahim Nooredine II (P87), providing the maternal royal link that legitimized his claim.\n\nChosen as sultan on January 22, 1954 and formally proclaimed on March 6, 1954, his regnal title Jalal ul-Malik Muhammad Farid al-Awwal Kathiri Maha Radun combined Arabic honorifics with the ancient Dhivehi royal designation. When the British protectorate ended on July 26, 1965, he assumed the grander title of "King" (His Majesty King Muhammad Farid the First), a short-lived elevation that lasted barely three years.\n\nHe married three times. The sultanate was abolished by national referendum on April 1, 1968, and the Republic of the Maldives was formally declared on November 11, 1968, ending a royal tradition that stretched back over eight centuries to the legendary Koimala. Mohamed Farid died in Male in May 1969, less than a year after the institution he had embodied ceased to exist.\n\nWith his passing, the Huraagey dynasty and the Maldivian sultanate became historical artifacts. The dynasty\'s extraordinary genealogical journey -- from the Hilaaly warlords of the fifteenth century, through a Catholic conversion in Portuguese Cochin, across five generations of Luso-Maldivian descent in Goa, to a liberation hero who expelled Malabar invaders, and finally to a constitutional monarch overtaken by republicanism -- encapsulates the full sweep of Maldivian political history.'
